{"/service/ndnp/oru/batch_oru_mallard_ver02/data/sn88086023/00202194679/1910082301/0585.xml":{"full_text":"DAILY EAST OREGOXIAN, PENDLETON, OREGON. TUESDAY, AVGl'ST 28, 110.\nEIGHT PAGES.\nAUTO CRAZE WORRIES\nFIRST SHOWING OF\nPAGE TWO.\nA\nHARPIES OF WALL ST.\nHOT\nIII\nFall Swifts\nThe Peoples Warehouse suprem\nacy was never more conclusively\nshown than in the exhibit of these\nnew suits now ready for your in\nspection. The stunning new models are all\nstrictly plain tailored; the skirts\nare plain tailored and close fitting\nThe most superior tailor made\ngarments shown in Pendleton.\n$25 to $50\nNEW MILLINERY SHOW\nHats that are right up to the minute in style, which\nyou may wear right now. Our millinery depart\nment is in full readiness for you now. We are show\ning many new exclusive novelties for fall.\nEach different style is proud of its own individuality\nEarly choosers will get the prizes. Don't fail to\ncall tomorrow, all at department store prices\nTHE PEOPLES WAREHOUSE\nWhere it Pays to Trade\n'W\nlift\nml\nByers'\nBest\nFlour\nIs made from the choicest wheat that\nerrors. Good bread i3 assured whsa\nBYERS' BEST FLOUR is used. Bran.\nShorn, Steam Rolled Barley always on\nhand.\nPendleton Roller Mills\nPendleton, Oregon.\nOroheum Theatre\n9. P. KEDERNACIL Proprietor\nHIGH-CLASS UP-TO-DATE MOTION\nPICTURES\nFor Men, Women and Children\nSEE PROGRAM IN TODAY'S PAPER.\nProgram Chance on Sunday. Tuesday's and Friday'.\nVALUABLE DLMOXDS\nSMUGGLED OX SHIP\nThe East Oregonian is eastern Oregon's representative paper. It\nleads and the people appreciate it and show it by their liberal patron\nace. It is the advertising medium of this section.\nBerlin. The papers announce that\nthe colonial office has received Infor\nmation that 2.000,000 marks worth of\ndiamonds have been smuggled In one\nhaul out of the colony involving the\nloss of 700.000 marks to the colonial\ntreasury. A detective employed In the\naffair has ascertained that the owners\nof the diamonds entrusted them to\ncertain women, who traveled from La\nderitz Bay to Capetown with the dia\nmonds hidden in their clothing. The\nvomen were arrested In Capetown,\nbut the diamonds were no longer In\ntheir possession. It is believed that\nthey were shipped on board the Ger\nman liner bound for Europe through\nthe connivance of the stewards. The\nliner left Capetown shortly before the\narrest of the women. On Its arrival\nh' the German port the ship will be\nsearched for diamonds. All diamonds\nexported from southwest Africa have\nto pay an export duty of 33 1-2 per\ncent ad valorem.\nBaby Morphine Fiends,\nare made by all soothing syrups and\nbaby medicines that contain opium\nand narcotics. McGee's Baby Elixir\ncontains no Injurious or narcotic\ndrugs of any kind. A sure and safe\ncure for disordered stomachs, bow\nels and fretfulness splendid for\nteething Infants. A. C. Koeppen\nBros.\nWITHDRAWS MILLIONS FROM\nSTOCK EXCHANGE CHAXXELS\nHowl F.iimnuU'S From limiuelal Muck\nt n in -1 localise Critic for \"Joy Wa\ngons' Tunis Aside Wealth Tlmt\nWould be Engulfed In Wall Street.\nNew York. Willi street estimates\nthat approximately $500,000,000 will\nbe spent this year by Americans for\nthe purchase of automobiles. Of this\nvast sum probably 85 per cent will\nhe for machines of domestic make.\nthe only foreign product In which\nwill be rubber for the tires, of which\nabout $75,000,000 will be used.\nIt is computed by statisticians of\nNew York's financial district that half\nof this outlay would be used for stock\nmarket speculation but for the nation\nwide craze for \"Joy cars.\" With such\nan enormous amount of money di\nverted from stock trading channels\nconditions In the street are now akin\nto those that prevailed during, the\n1907 ranlc. In six months there has\nbeen a shrinkage of $150,000,000 In\nthe market value of securities dealt\nin upon the stock exchange, due main\nly to lack of public support. The\nlambs, always a fruitful source of re\nvenue for the wily bulls and bears,\nno longer gambol with their old ab\nandon and have become ns scarce as\nhen's teeth about Wall. Nassau\nBroad streets. All that are left are\nthe professional traders to whom the\nlimited pickings are not over-attractive.\nIn the hope of checking the spread\nof the automobile tide, the assistance\nof local bankers has been enlisted.\nThe latter are now vociferously de\nprecating the mania. They claim It\nis inoculating the small business men\nof the country as well as the affluent\nmerchants of the city, and that In\norder to gratify their appetite for\nmachines this class Is mortgaging Its\nhomes and property. This cry of\nalarm however Is not borne out by\nthe mortgage records which show but\na normal state of borrowing on real\nestate. Neither do the reports of the\nclearing house Indicate that bank de\nposits are being appreciably with\ndrawn to enable customers to buy\nmachines. What money is being used\nby the public for the purchase of\ncars Is Its surplus cash which In\nother years found its way Into stock\nexchange houses for less exhllerat-\nIng employment. This Is the money\nthat created Inflated anl fictitious\nmarkets and enabled the gamblers of\nthe street to live in opulence while\ntheir clients grow two grey hairs\nwhere there was one before.\nThroughout the financial district.\nespecially among those who depend\nupon the outside for their business,\nthere seems to be a disposition to de\nplore the recent purchase by J. Pler\npont Morgan of the controlling inter\nest In one of the largest of the do\nmestic automobile factories. They\nthink it will have a bad effect on the\nmarket and help to retard the return\nof prosperity In the street by giving\nundue prestige to the Industry to\nwhose development they attribute\nmost of their troubles. Their chag\nrin recalls the feeling existing In the\ndistrict some years ago during one\nof the Intermittent periods of depres\nsion to which It Is subject, when John\nD. Rockefeller Instead of supporting\na declining market dumped several\nof his millions into the stock of the\nquick lunch restaurants of the big\neastern cities, which have since net\nted him handsome profits.\nIn reply to Wall street's lament\nanent the diversion of money from the\nstock market, the president of one of\nthe large automobile companies this\nweek threw a Jolt Into the enemy's\ncamp In a statement saying that ttie\npublic had grown tired of frittering\naway its savings In Wall street gamb\nling that rarely netted It anything\nbut headaches and Insomlna, and had\ndetermined to get some wholesome\npleasure out of Its cash through the\npurchase of machines that would en\nable them to give enjoyment and re\ncreation to others as well as to themselves.\nIn buying a cougn medicine, don't\nbe afraid to get Chamberlain's Cough\nRemedy. There Is no danger from It,\nand relief Is sure to follow. Especial\nly recommended for coughs, colds and\nwhooping cough. Sold by all dealer.\nOregon Theatre Tuesday, Aug. 23rd\nFIRST ATTRACTION OF THE SEASON\nA Corker in Cork One you all know and your fathers knew before you.\nRichard (f& Pringle's Famous Georgia\niil I 'ii' S jk\n7 (c\n9\n40-Kingpins of Minstrelsy-40 Mammoth Street Parade at Noon\nPrices $1.00, 75c 50c and 25c, Seat sale opens Monday morning, Aug. 22 at 10 o'clock at Pendleton Drug Co\nIS?\n&s3\nfiB\nALCOHOL 3 PER CENT.\nAVigeteblerTcparstlonfirAs\nstaIlarinilER)odanuRegula\nting the Sumacis andBowk of\nIVomotcsDigratlonJChtfuU'\nness and RratjContains nptttur\nOpiuiu.Marptune norMiamLi\nNOT NARCOTIC.\nfJtwSmJ-\nAdtitSJfl-\nCtrix4StMnr-mitmflanr.\nAperfect Remedy for Corcftf\ntlon Sour Stowkli.Dlarrtoa\nWorms .Convulsions Jewisfr\nness andLoss of Sleep.\nFacsimile Signature of\nNEW YORK.\nnuaranleed under the Food aA\nFor Infants and Children.\nThe Kind You Have\nAlways Bought\nBears the\nSignature\nof\nExact Copy of Wrapper.\nIn\nUse\nFor Over\nThirty Years\nTBI eMTu IHMNV, MCW YOU OITT\nNEWS OF TEE\nNORTHWEST\n............a\nNoted Muwlelnn Dead.\nSpokane, Wash. The funeral of\nProfessor Frank Bracht, musician of\nworld renown and holder of a medal\nfor bravery from the emperor of Ger\nmany, took place from his stately\ncountry home Sunday morning at\n9:30 o'clock.\nProfessor Bracht was born at\nFreiwaUle. Oermany, 65 years ago. At\ntho a bo of 18 he was a leader of a\nmilitary band in Berlin, and before\ncoming to America waa leader of the\nfamous Theodore Thomas- band, and\nlater treasurer of the ratrick Oil\nmore band. Aside from holding a\nmedal for bravery, Bracht was deco\nrated by Xapoleon III of France for\nproficiency as a flutist.\nSince coming to Spokane about 30\nyears ago Bracht founded the Con\ncordia Singing society, and was In\nstructor of music at Oonzaga college\nhere. One of the largest funerals In\nthe city's history was had, as many\nmusical enthusiasts from the coast\nand east are coming to attend.\nBracht died Thursday from paralysis.\nPorter Kliot4 Woman.\nSeattle. Sadie Hicks, colored, 26\nyearB of age. with three serious bullet\nwounds, Is lying between life and\ndeath at the city hospital.\n\"Sadie, your time has come,\" cried\nVirgil Young, a negro porter, as he\nmet the Hicks woman In front of a\nYesler Way drug store Sunday after\nnoon The street was crowded with\npeople on their way to the baseball\ngame. Young emptied his revolver at\nthe negro woman, calmly stopped, re\nloaded and began firing again. Of\nthe 12 bullets, nine went wild and\nscattered the crowds. Men and wo\nmen dropped to the pavement or hid\nbehind trees.- One passerby returned\nthe porter's fire.\nThe woman ran Into a drug store\nand dropped, with a wound Just below\nthe heart. One bullet passed entirely\nthrough her body, another entered tho\nright eye and passed through the head\nmissing the brain, and a third had\nentered the temple.\nYoung surrendered peacefully.\nHawley arrived In Lakeview on Ms\ntour of the First district and received\na very cool reception from the resi\ndents here, who are opposed, for the\nmost part, to any of the men with the\n\"Joe Cannon\" brand that are run\nning In connection with the Southern\nPacific crowd, headed by Bowerman.\nHis meeting at the court house was\nfairly well attended, but the audience\ngave little indication of being in sym\npathy with the speaker.\nDysentery is a dangerous disease\nbut can be cured. Chamberlain's Col.\nIc, Cholera and Diarrhoea Remedy\nhas been successfully used In nine\nepidemics of dyserury. It has never\nbeen known to fall. It Is equally val\nuable for children and adults, and\nwhen reduced with water and sweet\nened, it is pleasant to take. Sold by\nall dealers,\nGladness comes with a better under\nStanding of the transient nature of the\nmany physical Ills which vanish be\nfore proper efforts gentle efforts\"\npleasant efforts rightly directed and\nassisted by the pleasant laxative rem\nedy Syrup of Figs and Elixir of Senna.\nIts beneficial effects are due to the\nfact that it is the one remedy which\npromotes Internal cleanliness without\ndebilitating the organs on which it\nacts. To get its beneficial effects al\nways buy the genuine manufactured\nby the California Fig Syrup Co.\nDayton Wheat Moves.\nDayton, Wash. The calm in the\ngrain market situation here was ab\nruptly dispelled Sunday when Port\nland and Puget sound buyers loaded\nOn the cars for immediate shipment\nto tidewater 30.000 bushels of grain\nfollowing word from Portland that\nthis amount was wanted.\nThis is tho first shipment of new\ngrain leaving this part of Washing\nton and dealers consider it means that\nheavy shipping will commence short\nly. Columbia county rarmcrs have\nsuddenly changed their minds, too,\nabout selling and are now offering\ntheir crops. But representatives of\ncoast exporters predict a marked\nweakening of the market within a\nweek and refuso to stock heavily at\npresent prices. Grain is now coming\ninto warehouses here at the rate of\n100,000 a bushel a day.\nApple Record Will Break.\nWalla Walla, Wash. All apple\nshlpplng recordB established In the\nTouchet valley will be broken this\nyear, according to the statement of\nB. I. Young, a representative of the\nNorthwest Fruitgrowers' exchange,\nwho was In the city the latter part of!\nthe week. Ho estimates that ISO cars\nwill be shipped from that end of the\nWalla Wntln country, and nearly all\nof these will be raised In the three\nbig orchards of that section Pomona\nnear Dayton, Taggard's near Walts\nburg, and Klmlgren's at Prescott.\nFort St. James\nOa Lake Stuart,\nBRITISH COLUMBIA\nThis Is destined to be the Portland\n3f British Columbia, on a 'navigable\nriver and deep water lake with two\ntrains running In next fall.\nLetters pour Into our office all day\nwith applications for lota. To those\nwho cannot come In we would do onr\nutmost to make a good selection.\nPrice tl00 and 1200 each. Cash\nm.00. balance $10.00 a month. A\nfew 40 acre farms joining Fort Bt.\nJames townslte and Lake Stuart,\n150.00 cash and 110.00 a month.\nVon need not be a Canadian Cl tiara\nto Hold This.\nYou need not improve It, nor yon\nneed not reside on It. All this land\nIs on or near the railroad. Grand\nTrunk Pacific, Alaska Yukon, and\nCanadian Northern railroads.\nRich farm lands, 18.60 per acre,\n13.00 cash, and balance f 1.00 per acre\nper year until paid.\nAPPLY CANADIAN NORTHERN\nLAND COMPANY,\nS04, SOS and 808 Lewis Bnlldlng,\nPortland. Oregon.\nFRESH MEATS\nSAUSAGES. FUJI ANB\nLARD.\nAlways pure and delivered\npromptly, If you phon the\nCentral Meat Market\n10S E. Alta 8t, Phone Main II.\nIfawley Gets Cool Reception.\nLakeview, Or. Congressman W. C.","height":"27484","width":"19464"}}
